1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:01:32,640 --> 00:01:36,474
<i>A million baby kisses I'll deliver</i>

3
00:01:37,800 --> 00:01:41,634
<i>If you will only sing the</i> Swanee River

4
00:01:41,760 --> 00:01:46,311
<i>Rock-a-bye your rock-a-bye baby</i>

5
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:52,271
<i>With a Dixie melody</i>

6
00:02:02,360 --> 00:02:03,998
- Julie?
- She has left, sir.

7
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:06,950
- When? Where to? Was she packed?
- Yes, sir.

8
00:02:07,080 --> 00:02:08,798
- How long ago?
- About half an hour ago.

9
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:12,230
- Do you know where, Henry?
- All I know is the airport.

10
00:02:12,640 --> 00:02:14,358
- New York.
- She wouldn't let me take her...

11
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:17,597
Thanks. Steve, see what you can get me
on the next plane out of here.

12
00:02:17,720 --> 00:02:20,837
Do it, will you?
Henry, get me some stuff in a bag.

13
00:02:25,720 --> 00:02:27,199
I don't get it.

14
00:02:27,800 --> 00:02:31,076
If something was on her mind,
why not wait and talk?

15
00:02:32,120 --> 00:02:35,032
You don't just get up and go.
It does not make sense.

16
00:02:35,240 --> 00:02:39,836
And my pal Steve lets me stand out there
and sing my brains out for another hour.

17
00:02:39,960 --> 00:02:41,234
Why doesn't he tell me?

18
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:45,239
Haven't I got a right to know
when she gets a crazy notion like this?

19
00:02:45,360 --> 00:02:47,920
- Do you think it was so sudden?
- What else?

20
00:02:48,880 --> 00:02:51,917
I am thinking of the questions
she asked tonight.

21
00:02:52,280 --> 00:02:54,555
- What questions?
- Were you happy?

22
00:02:54,760 --> 00:02:57,069
Did you think of singing anymore?

23
00:02:57,200 --> 00:02:59,156
I have told her a thousand times.

24
00:02:59,280 --> 00:03:02,078
You told her,
and tonight she heard you sing.

25
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:04,389
So what?

26
00:03:05,880 --> 00:03:10,158
You saw it coming, Papa.
And Steve, everybody but me.

27
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:13,038
All right, so I sang.

28
00:03:13,160 --> 00:03:15,116
The crowd was yelling,
she told me to go ahead.

29
00:03:15,240 --> 00:03:17,071
So I got wound up a little.

30
00:03:17,200 --> 00:03:19,350
I told her, it does not mean
a thing to me anymore.

31
00:03:19,480 --> 00:03:21,948
I was happy this way, the way we were.

32
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:25,358
- Steve, how about it?
- Give me time, will you?

33
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:30,676
It is going to be all right, Mamma.

34
00:03:30,800 --> 00:03:33,109
I hate to run away like this
on your anniversary party.

35
00:03:33,240 --> 00:03:36,516
If not for my party,
if I did not have to see a night club...

36
00:03:36,640 --> 00:03:37,550
Mamma...

37
00:03:37,680 --> 00:03:40,114
Fine! Now we got tears,
everything is solved.

38
00:03:40,240 --> 00:03:42,834
- Congratulations, Mamma.
- Mamma, don't be silly.

39
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:45,315
Don't you see,
whether we'd had the party or not...

40
00:03:45,440 --> 00:03:48,432
You're all set. If you're going to make it,
you better get going.

41
00:03:50,920 --> 00:03:52,399
It's ready, sir.

42
00:03:56,360 --> 00:03:57,839
Goodbye, Mamma.

43
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:02,752
I do not know how long I will be gone.
If I do not get back soon...

44
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:05,838
anytime you want to go home,
Steve will take care of everything.

45
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:08,394
And I will see you in Washington, maybe.

46
00:04:08,520 --> 00:04:11,796
Take care of yourself, Mamma.
You, too, Papa.

47
00:04:12,760 --> 00:04:14,352
So long, Tom, Steve.

48
00:04:14,480 --> 00:04:17,358
Wait a second,
I am driving you to the airport.

49
00:04:24,360 --> 00:04:26,316
<i>You may think you mean it, Al...</i>

50
00:04:26,440 --> 00:04:29,193
<i>but you will never be happy</i>
<i>away from show business.</i>

51
00:04:29,320 --> 00:04:32,710
<i>And someday, if I ever feel</i>
<i>you quit just for my sake...</i>

52
00:04:33,720 --> 00:04:37,156
<i>if I am ever sure you want to sing,</i>
<i>more than you want me...</i>

53
00:04:44,480 --> 00:04:46,994
No, I am telling you, Steve,
there is not a trace of her.

54
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:49,714
She got here all right,
but didn't check in anyplace.

55
00:04:49,840 --> 00:04:52,195
I have turned the town upside down.

56
00:04:52,320 --> 00:04:55,471
She hopped in a car, I guess,
and just disappeared.

57
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:58,439
Steve, I need you.
How about you coming here?

58
00:04:58,560 --> 00:05:01,233
<i>- I will be there tomorrow.</i>
- Good, I am waiting for you.

59
00:05:01,360 --> 00:05:03,112
<i>- So long, Al.</i>
- So long.

60
00:05:10,560 --> 00:05:13,791
Maybe I don't know my own mind,
but she was what I wanted.

61
00:05:13,920 --> 00:05:17,515
The only thing I ever got for myself
outside of show racket.

62
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:21,553
But I guess I've just been kidding myself.

63
00:05:21,800 --> 00:05:25,759
Love, a girl, a couple of words
I must have picked up out of a song.

64
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:29,513
If she says so,
I've been dying to sing all the time.

65
00:05:29,640 --> 00:05:32,108
All I ever wanted was a cheering mob.

66
00:05:32,440 --> 00:05:35,557
I will say this about the cheering mob:
That was love, brother.

67
00:05:35,680 --> 00:05:38,353
For 20 years,
nobody ever walked out on me.

68
00:05:40,320 --> 00:05:44,472
Okay, if she says so, I am back where I was.
Singing for a living.

69
00:05:45,560 --> 00:05:47,471
And it ain't a bad feeling.

70
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:50,956
The only question now is:
How fast can I get back to work?

71
00:05:51,080 --> 00:05:54,197
Tom, that script of yours
I read the other day back home, it's good.

72
00:05:54,320 --> 00:05:58,472
That's the show I'd like to do, if you'll
take a chance with a character like me.

73
00:05:58,720 --> 00:06:01,154
- I'll consider it.
- I want to start right away.

74
00:06:01,280 --> 00:06:03,316
- First thing tomorrow.
- Why not tonight?

75
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:05,874
Why don't we kick it around?
Where's the script?

76
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,195
- I don't walk around with it.
- Let us get it.

77
00:06:08,320 --> 00:06:10,311
Why didn't I bring the one
we had in California?

78
00:06:10,440 --> 00:06:11,793
You mean this one?

79
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:15,034
You dog. Come to papa.

80
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:32,510
<i>Is it true what they say about Dixie?</i>

81
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:37,150
<i>Does the sun really shine all the time?</i>

82
00:06:38,640 --> 00:06:42,952
<i>Do the sweet magnolias blossom</i>
<i>at everybody's door?</i>

83
00:06:43,120 --> 00:06:47,159
<i>And do folks keep eating possum</i>
<i>till they can't eat no more?</i>

84
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:50,996
<i>Is it true what they say about Swanee?</i>

85
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:55,596
<i>Is a dream by that stream so sublime?</i>

86
00:06:56,760 --> 00:07:01,231
<i>Do they laugh, do they love</i>
<i>like they do in every song?</i>

87
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:05,319
<i>If it's true, that is where I belong</i>

88
00:07:07,480 --> 00:07:10,392
<i>I said do they laugh</i>

89
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:15,473
<i>Do they love</i>

90
00:07:17,880 --> 00:07:23,557
<i>like they do in every song?</i>

91
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:27,228
That's pretty.

92
00:07:27,440 --> 00:07:32,560
<i>If it's true, that is where I belong</i>

93
00:08:09,760 --> 00:08:11,159
Al, you're on.

94
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:26,349
<i>The bells are ringing for me and my gal</i>

95
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:31,309
<i>The birds are singing for me and my gal</i>

96
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:36,273
<i>Everybody's been knowing</i>
<i>to a wedding they are going</i>

97
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:41,710
<i>And for weeks they've been sewing</i>
<i>every Susie and Sal</i>

98
00:08:41,920 --> 00:08:45,708
<i>They are congregating for me and my gal</i>

99
00:08:46,880 --> 00:08:51,351
<i>The parson is waiting for me and my gal</i>

100
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:54,558
<i>And sometime, I am going to build</i>
<i>a little home for two</i>

101
00:08:54,680 --> 00:08:56,716
<i>for three or four or more</i>

102
00:08:57,080 --> 00:09:00,993
<i>In Loveland, for me and my gal</i>

103
00:09:05,080 --> 00:09:08,709
<i>The bells are ringing for me and my gal</i>

104
00:09:09,720 --> 00:09:13,349
<i>The birds are singing for me and my gal</i>

105
00:09:13,480 --> 00:09:16,711
<i>And sometime, I am going to build</i>
<i>a little home for two</i>

106
00:09:16,840 --> 00:09:18,717
<i>or three or four or more</i>

107
00:09:18,840 --> 00:09:23,834
<i>In Loveland, for me and my gal</i>

108
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:35,553
If you do not mind, that's all tonight.

109
00:09:38,600 --> 00:09:40,079
What's the matter, Al?

110
00:09:42,480 --> 00:09:45,074
Go on with the show.
Leave me out of the finale.

111
00:09:50,640 --> 00:09:53,871
I tell you, nothing is the matter.
Just comes a night that...

112
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:55,956
How long can you go on
knocking yourself out?

113
00:09:56,080 --> 00:09:58,230
For what? Their $4 and their applause?

114
00:09:59,960 --> 00:10:02,076
Holy smoke! Don't know what hit me.

115
00:10:02,200 --> 00:10:05,795
- I never walked off like that in my life.
- What's the matter, Al?

116
00:10:06,280 --> 00:10:09,511
I just can't take it anymore.
I used to live for this.

117
00:10:10,520 --> 00:10:13,193
The kick is gone. It is just hard work now.

118
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:17,829
So what am I killing myself for?
What am I getting out of it?

119
00:10:18,960 --> 00:10:21,633
You were always telling me,
how about something for myself?

120
00:10:21,760 --> 00:10:25,150
How about it? That's what I want now,
some laughs, fun.

121
00:10:25,280 --> 00:10:26,599
Just for me.

122
00:10:29,400 --> 00:10:31,072
What happened to you?

123
00:10:31,600 --> 00:10:34,751
Sit down, Tom.
I think we got some news for you.

124
00:10:46,760 --> 00:10:49,957
The boy is sick, Papa.
This he tries to hide from us.

125
00:10:51,480 --> 00:10:53,914
- Papa, you agree or not?
- I agree.

126
00:10:54,080 --> 00:10:55,559
So why do you sit?

127
00:10:55,680 --> 00:10:58,558
Because it is a sickness not for doctors.

128
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:00,632
Please, no riddles.

129
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:04,032
Mamma, just go on pasting
in Asa's scrapbook.

130
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:05,593
You will understand.

131
00:11:14,440 --> 00:11:17,318
Where will he get
a good Jewish meal over there, Papa?

132
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:22,230
Mamma, without Jewish meals,
Gentiles are surviving year after year.

133
00:11:25,280 --> 00:11:26,508
Monte Carlo.

134
00:11:26,640 --> 00:11:29,837
Before they take your money away,
they make you dress up yet.

135
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:38,519
I saw a dozen bluebirds today
in the back yard. And he is looking.

136
00:11:41,920 --> 00:11:43,876
A girl with Asa. Who is it?

137
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:46,515
And if you knew, Mamma,
what would you know?

138
00:11:48,920 --> 00:11:53,152
- Again a new girl.
- Mamma, with a man it's only natural.

139
00:12:00,400 --> 00:12:03,517
- This is soup.
- Eat. You'll have another plate.

140
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:06,309
You don't know, Steve,
how we appreciate your visits.

141
00:12:06,440 --> 00:12:08,112
I just come for the food.

142
00:12:08,360 --> 00:12:10,271
For what it costs to come from New York...

143
00:12:10,400 --> 00:12:12,470
you could buy a better meal than this.

144
00:12:13,120 --> 00:12:15,998
So, this winter,
it's again Florida for Asa.

145
00:12:16,120 --> 00:12:19,430
- He's having a great time.
- Yeah, so he always says.

146
00:12:19,680 --> 00:12:21,557
Wait, do you hear? The radio.

147
00:12:21,680 --> 00:12:25,355
All day long, a Mr. Bing Crosby.

148
00:12:25,880 --> 00:12:27,996
Yes, he's doing all right.

149
00:12:28,960 --> 00:12:29,870
Crooning.

150
00:12:34,160 --> 00:12:36,196
- Very good.
- That's also singing.

151
00:12:36,560 --> 00:12:40,075
And the name "Bing." Go explain people.

152
00:12:40,400 --> 00:12:42,709
- But he's got something.
- Yes.

153
00:12:43,640 --> 00:12:44,959
He's got something.

154
00:12:45,080 --> 00:12:48,709
There was a time they played Asa's records.
That was a joy.

155
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:52,715
But for years now,
you would think Asa isn't alive anymore.

156
00:12:52,960 --> 00:12:54,473
All right, Mamma.

157
00:12:55,160 --> 00:12:57,993
We're eating, not singing. Give him the fish.

158
00:12:58,720 --> 00:13:02,599
This week it's very good, Steve.
And a little horseradish?

159
00:13:03,600 --> 00:13:05,989
There. But be careful.

160
00:13:06,240 --> 00:13:10,153
Don't worry. This stuff got me once.
But I take it easy now.

161
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:12,874
Very easy.

162
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:18,273
I am afraid this week it was extra strong.

163
00:13:18,640 --> 00:13:21,108
On his back, Papa. I'll bring the chicken.

164
00:13:39,120 --> 00:13:41,236
Buying a horse, that I understand.

165
00:13:41,440 --> 00:13:45,115
But buying a fighter, a human being.
How is this, Papa?

166
00:13:45,560 --> 00:13:48,199
Foolishness, a tragedy, that's how it is.

167
00:13:49,160 --> 00:13:52,357
A whole world is on fire,
a Hitler swallows nations...

168
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:56,952
millions of our people driven, tortured,
killed like flies.

169
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:00,150
You do not want to sing, all right.

170
00:14:00,320 --> 00:14:02,834
But horses, fighters!

171
00:14:15,880 --> 00:14:18,348
Hello, Cantor. This is Steve.

172
00:14:18,880 --> 00:14:20,677
Tell me first, is Mamma any better?

173
00:14:21,080 --> 00:14:23,674
I am afraid not.
The pneumonia came so fast.

174
00:14:23,800 --> 00:14:24,869
Did you reach Asa?

175
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:28,470
No. I called Havana twice.
He is off cruising on somebody's boat.

176
00:14:28,600 --> 00:14:30,875
They are getting in touch with him by radio.

177
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:34,629
I don't know how long it'll take him
to sail back to Havana and catch a plane.

178
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:37,639
- You will keep trying, please.
- Sure I will.

179
00:14:37,880 --> 00:14:39,836
Thank you very much, Steve.

180
00:14:40,400 --> 00:14:41,355
Bye.

181
00:16:46,720 --> 00:16:48,392
You all right, Papa?

182
00:16:53,480 --> 00:16:55,232
I wish I had been here.

183
00:16:56,760 --> 00:16:58,432
She understood, Asa.

184
00:16:59,080 --> 00:17:01,150
No sense to feel sorry.

185
00:17:03,680 --> 00:17:05,671
That was a prayer for Mamma.

186
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:08,116
For Mamma, and all our people.

187
00:17:09,280 --> 00:17:11,919
For their suffering, like millions today.

188
00:17:13,240 --> 00:17:14,355
I know.

189
00:17:17,400 --> 00:17:18,310
You do?

190
00:17:20,480 --> 00:17:21,708
Come, Asa.

191
00:17:37,160 --> 00:17:38,149
Sit down, Asa.

192
00:17:38,280 --> 00:17:41,716
I'll get you something, something to eat,
or maybe a cold drink.

193
00:17:42,080 --> 00:17:44,674
No, thanks, Papa, I don't want anything.

194
00:17:45,800 --> 00:17:49,952
- Who looks after you here now?
- Someone comes in.

195
00:17:50,360 --> 00:17:53,875
It is all arranged.
I think I have to lie down for a few minutes.

196
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:55,752
- Just on the couch.
- Sure, go ahead.

197
00:17:55,880 --> 00:17:58,155
- Just a few minutes. You'll stay?
- Of course I will.

198
00:17:58,280 --> 00:18:01,078
- I am going to call Steve in New York.
- Fine.

199
00:18:05,120 --> 00:18:07,190
How about coming away with me
for a while?

200
00:18:07,320 --> 00:18:09,959
- Take a little trip somewhere.
- We are in the war now.

201
00:18:10,080 --> 00:18:13,231
- This is no time for trips.
- A week or so, just for a change.

202
00:18:14,200 --> 00:18:15,474
Thank you.

203
00:18:15,640 --> 00:18:19,792
But prize fights, racetracks,
that change I wouldn't need.

204
00:18:20,360 --> 00:18:23,397
- Why do you say that, Papa?
- I merely said a fact.

205
00:18:23,640 --> 00:18:27,235
- You hate everything I've been doing.
- It's your life to throw away.

206
00:18:27,960 --> 00:18:29,871
What do you want me to do?

207
00:18:30,400 --> 00:18:32,277
Who can tell another man?

208
00:18:32,600 --> 00:18:35,398
You want me to get in the war
and fight at my age?

209
00:18:35,520 --> 00:18:37,829
A man finds ways to do everything.

210
00:18:38,520 --> 00:18:41,159
But if he is so busy fighting himself...

211
00:18:43,760 --> 00:18:45,398
We will talk later.

212
00:18:49,400 --> 00:18:50,355
Hello?

213
00:18:51,920 --> 00:18:54,992
Oh, he's not? Will he... Come in.

214
00:18:55,560 --> 00:18:58,518
Leave word for Mr. Martin
to call Washington, this number...

215
00:18:58,640 --> 00:19:00,232
anytime before 11:00.

216
00:19:00,640 --> 00:19:02,995
- That's right. Thanks.
- I'll do that.

217
00:19:03,920 --> 00:19:05,194
Why, you...

218
00:19:06,360 --> 00:19:07,236
Hello, Al.

219
00:19:07,360 --> 00:19:08,839
- How are you?
- Fine.

220
00:19:09,120 --> 00:19:11,429
- When did you get in?
- About an hour ago.

221
00:19:11,560 --> 00:19:13,835
- How is Papa doing?
- Pretty good, Steve.

222
00:19:14,440 --> 00:19:16,715
He is taking a nap in there, right now.

223
00:19:17,240 --> 00:19:18,593
Yeah, he is fine.

224
00:19:18,840 --> 00:19:20,751
Sit down, tell me the news.

225
00:19:20,880 --> 00:19:23,997
- What are you doing around here?
- I got a date in 15 minutes.

226
00:19:24,120 --> 00:19:25,599
This time of night?

227
00:19:25,720 --> 00:19:28,951
I flew down to see a bunch of generals
at the war department.

228
00:19:29,080 --> 00:19:31,514
- Who?
- Son, I have enlisted.

229
00:19:31,960 --> 00:19:34,428
Enlisted! Why you're four times
older than I am!

230
00:19:34,560 --> 00:19:37,791
- Don't tell me you're going to fight.
- Sure, from behind a desk.

231
00:19:37,920 --> 00:19:41,799
- Quit kidding. What is this about?
- Entertainment for the kids overseas.

232
00:19:41,920 --> 00:19:44,388
- Getting shows together?
- A little more than that.

233
00:19:44,520 --> 00:19:47,751
You see, lots of entertainers
are over there now. Good talent.

234
00:19:47,880 --> 00:19:50,235
But they got to have more, and the best.

235
00:19:50,360 --> 00:19:54,512
Those kids are stuck away in
Pacific jungles, Aleutians, Africa, Iceland.

236
00:19:55,360 --> 00:19:59,148
It'd be a terrific boost to morale
if they could get the top names to go over.

237
00:19:59,280 --> 00:20:01,714
The biggest performers in the country.

238
00:20:01,840 --> 00:20:04,070
That is the job they want me to tackle.

239
00:20:04,360 --> 00:20:07,193
I guess they figured
if I could manage Jolson for 20 years...

240
00:20:07,320 --> 00:20:08,992
I can lick anything.

241
00:20:09,440 --> 00:20:12,432
Yeah, they're right.
You won't have any trouble, Steve.

242
00:20:12,560 --> 00:20:14,835
Big name stars will go
once they know what's needed.

243
00:20:14,960 --> 00:20:17,633
It's just a question of getting
a few of them to lead the way.

244
00:20:17,760 --> 00:20:21,435
Sure. Darned big job, Steve.
I am proud of you.

245
00:20:21,840 --> 00:20:23,239
Save it, pal.

246
00:20:24,320 --> 00:20:26,754
You know, seven or eight years ago...

247
00:20:27,280 --> 00:20:29,635
I could've been the guy
to start this thing off.

248
00:20:29,760 --> 00:20:32,718
- What's the matter with now?
- Don't be silly.

249
00:20:33,320 --> 00:20:36,278
These kids are hep.
They want the stuff they heard back home.

250
00:20:36,400 --> 00:20:39,517
The top guys they know.
How many of them know me now?

251
00:20:39,640 --> 00:20:43,315
But everybody in show business does.
And they have followed you before.

252
00:20:44,480 --> 00:20:46,357
I'm thinking of the kids.

253
00:20:48,480 --> 00:20:50,436
You know, I better get going.

254
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:54,109
- See you here later?
- Yeah.

255
00:20:54,720 --> 00:20:55,994
So long, Al.

256
00:21:01,480 --> 00:21:03,277
Maybe I'll walk over with you.

257
00:21:41,520 --> 00:21:44,114
All right, boys, hold it. Hold it.

258
00:21:46,880 --> 00:21:49,235
We are going to have a lot of fun tonight.

259
00:21:49,360 --> 00:21:52,830
They've been telling us we're gonna
get some big entertainers up here.

260
00:21:52,960 --> 00:21:56,191
And believe it or not,
we've got one of them with us right now.

261
00:22:00,320 --> 00:22:03,869
In fact, when I heard this man was coming,
I said:

262
00:22:04,320 --> 00:22:06,629
"They are making good in a big way."

263
00:22:06,880 --> 00:22:09,030
I don't know what the name means to you...

264
00:22:09,160 --> 00:22:12,675
but when I was your age,
it meant the world's greatest entertainer.

265
00:22:12,800 --> 00:22:14,028
Al Jolson.

266
00:22:23,840 --> 00:22:26,877
Thanks, Colonel.
If I am half as good as that send-off...

267
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:29,389
I may leave here a second lieutenant.

268
00:22:31,280 --> 00:22:33,271
Hello, gang. I sing.

269
00:22:33,760 --> 00:22:37,036
If you don't believe me,
write and ask your grandmothers.

270
00:22:37,280 --> 00:22:39,510
It is wonderful working for guys like you...

271
00:22:39,640 --> 00:22:43,189
'cause if you don't like it,
where can you go? It is me or nothing.

272
00:22:44,320 --> 00:22:45,912
All kidding aside, fellows...

273
00:22:46,040 --> 00:22:49,669
my stuff isn't what you were hearing
back home when you left...

274
00:22:49,960 --> 00:22:53,077
but you might like an old one,
the way they used to do them.

275
00:22:53,400 --> 00:22:54,628
Orchestra.

276
00:23:00,600 --> 00:23:04,718
<i>We leave home expecting to find a bluebird</i>

277
00:23:05,880 --> 00:23:10,635
<i>Hoping every cloud will be silver-lined</i>

278
00:23:11,480 --> 00:23:14,790
<i>But we all return</i>

279
00:23:15,160 --> 00:23:19,073
<i>And as we live, we learn</i>

280
00:23:19,440 --> 00:23:25,151
<i>That we left our happiness behind</i>

281
00:23:29,600 --> 00:23:33,388
<i>The bird with</i>

282
00:23:33,680 --> 00:23:36,478
<i>feathers of blue</i>

283
00:23:37,840 --> 00:23:40,035
<i>Is waiting for you</i>

284
00:23:41,480 --> 00:23:45,473
<i>Back in your own backyard</i>

285
00:23:46,800 --> 00:23:50,554
<i>You'll see your castle in Spain</i>

286
00:23:52,040 --> 00:23:54,031
<i>Through your windowpane</i>

287
00:23:55,560 --> 00:24:00,190
<i>Back in your own backyard</i>

288
00:24:00,680 --> 00:24:04,912
<i>Oh, you can go to the east</i>
<i>Go to the west</i>

289
00:24:05,760 --> 00:24:07,637
<i>Someday you'll come</i>

290
00:24:08,800 --> 00:24:10,472
<i>Weary at heart</i>

291
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:13,433
<i>Back where you started from</i>

292
00:24:14,440 --> 00:24:18,399
<i>You'll find your happiness lies</i>

293
00:24:19,760 --> 00:24:22,399
<i>Right under your eyes</i>

294
00:24:23,080 --> 00:24:28,677
<i>Back in your own backyard</i>

295
00:24:41,640 --> 00:24:43,676
Big boot singing to those kids tonight.

296
00:24:43,800 --> 00:24:45,870
I guess they thought I was a little old-timey.

297
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:48,275
They loved it. You heard them yell.

298
00:24:48,400 --> 00:24:51,915
Yeah, I guess, it was just the idea
of something from home.

299
00:24:52,920 --> 00:24:55,309
- Is that my plane?
- They'll call you.

300
00:24:59,400 --> 00:25:02,437
- You ought to relax.
- How do you do that, Colonel?

301
00:25:03,320 --> 00:25:06,437
It is kind of tough doing this,
after laying off a long time...

302
00:25:06,560 --> 00:25:08,949
and not sure you're getting over,
that's what kills you.

303
00:25:09,080 --> 00:25:12,277
You did not get over any better in Duluth,
20 years ago.

304
00:25:13,120 --> 00:25:16,999
- Minnesota, that's where I first heard you.
- Well, I'll be darned.

305
00:25:17,320 --> 00:25:19,788
- The old Lyceum Theatre.
- That's right.

306
00:25:20,120 --> 00:25:21,951
It gets a little chilly in Duluth.

307
00:25:22,080 --> 00:25:25,072
I played hooky from high school once
to see <i>Robinson Crusoe</i>.

308
00:25:25,200 --> 00:25:26,872
Oh, boy. That's going way back.

309
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:30,037
To me, you were the greatest thing
that ever lived.

310
00:25:31,360 --> 00:25:32,475
Thanks.

311
00:25:32,880 --> 00:25:35,110
Did you sneak in
that afternoon or did you pay?

312
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:37,231
- Pay.
- Then that's all right.

313
00:25:38,040 --> 00:25:42,192
First time I hit New York, the only thing
I wanted to do was go to the theatre...

314
00:25:42,320 --> 00:25:43,435
to see you.

315
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:47,037
Now I understand about tonight.
You're just an old fan.

316
00:25:47,160 --> 00:25:49,355
I could've knocked you over
reciting <i>Little Bo Peep</i>.

317
00:25:49,480 --> 00:25:50,674
Yeah, you could.

318
00:25:51,760 --> 00:25:53,830
- Ready to take off, sir.
- Thank you.

319
00:25:54,600 --> 00:25:56,113
Well, here we go.

320
00:25:57,360 --> 00:25:59,954
Look, Colonel,
tell the boys I'll try to get back.

321
00:26:00,160 --> 00:26:04,312
Tell them a lot of big stars
will be along soon, but not to forget me.

322
00:26:04,520 --> 00:26:07,193
They'll never forget
you were one of the early ones.

323
00:26:07,320 --> 00:26:08,878
That is something.

324
00:26:10,320 --> 00:26:11,878
Colonel Bryant, you've been wonderful.

325
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:14,753
- Hope we meet up someday back home.
- I hope we do.

326
00:26:15,480 --> 00:26:18,119
In fact, if you are ever in Hollywood...

327
00:26:18,360 --> 00:26:21,511
- Hollywood? Movies?
- I produced a few.

328
00:26:22,480 --> 00:26:23,879
That's a funny one.

329
00:26:24,200 --> 00:26:28,113
- I played in a few of them in my time.
- I remember every one of them.

330
00:26:29,280 --> 00:26:32,511
I'm afraid I do, too.
So long, Duluth. Good luck.

331
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:34,835
So long, Mr. Jolson. Good luck to you.

332
00:26:53,040 --> 00:26:55,873
<i>I'm looking over a four-leaf clover</i>

333
00:26:56,120 --> 00:26:59,476
<i>That I overlooked before</i>

334
