<i>His own sweet song</i>

343
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:33,709
<i>Oh, wake up, you sleepy head, get up</i>

344
00:27:34,600 --> 00:27:35,999
<i>Get out of bed, cheer up</i>

345
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:40,231
<i>The sun is red</i>
<i>Live, love, laugh, and be happy</i>

346
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:44,672
<i>What if I'd been blue?</i>
<i>Now I am walking through fields of flowers</i>

347
00:27:44,920 --> 00:27:49,198
<i>Rain may glisten</i>
<i>but still I listen for hours and hours</i>

348
00:27:49,720 --> 00:27:52,314
<i>I'm just a kid again</i>
<i>Doing what I did again</i>

349
00:27:52,440 --> 00:27:53,998
<i>singing a song</i>

350
00:27:54,120 --> 00:27:57,999
<i>When the red, red robin</i>
<i>Comes bob, bob, bobbing along</i>

351
00:27:58,800 --> 00:28:01,872
<i>When the red, red robin</i>
<i>Comes bobbing along</i>

352
00:28:03,200 --> 00:28:06,192
<i>Give my regards to Broadway</i>

353
00:28:06,320 --> 00:28:08,993
<i>Remember me to Herald Square</i>

354
00:28:09,880 --> 00:28:12,872
<i>Tell all the gang at 42nd Street</i>

355
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:15,992
<i>That I will soon be there</i>

356
00:28:16,240 --> 00:28:19,357
<i>Whisper of how I'm yearning</i>

357
00:28:19,520 --> 00:28:22,637
<i>To mingle with the old-time throng</i>

358
00:28:23,080 --> 00:28:25,753
<i>Give my regards to old Broadway</i>

359
00:28:25,880 --> 00:28:28,633
<i>and say that I'll be there e'er long</i>

360
00:28:30,280 --> 00:28:32,396
<i>Chinatown, my Chinatown</i>

361
00:28:33,800 --> 00:28:35,631
<i>Where the lights are low</i>

362
00:28:37,200 --> 00:28:39,191
<i>Hearts that know no other land</i>

363
00:28:40,640 --> 00:28:42,471
<i>Drifting to and fro</i>

364
00:28:44,200 --> 00:28:46,509
<i>Dreamy, dreamy Chinatown</i>

365
00:28:47,640 --> 00:28:50,712
<i>Almond eyes of brown</i>

366
00:28:51,360 --> 00:28:54,909
<i>Hearts seem light, and life seems bright</i>

367
00:28:55,680 --> 00:28:59,639
<i>In dreamy, dreamy China</i>
<i>Dreamy, dreamy China</i>

368
00:29:00,960 --> 00:29:04,589
<i>China, Chinatown</i>

369
00:29:05,400 --> 00:29:07,118
<i>I'm just wild about Harry</i>

370
00:29:08,120 --> 00:29:10,190
<i>Harry's wild about me</i>

371
00:29:10,800 --> 00:29:13,792
<i>The heavenly blisses of his kisses</i>

372
00:29:14,040 --> 00:29:15,917
<i>fill me with ecstasy</i>

373
00:29:16,600 --> 00:29:19,114
<i>He's sweet just like chocolate candy</i>

374
00:29:20,040 --> 00:29:22,156
<i>and like honey from the bee</i>

375
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:25,798
<i>I'm just wild about Harry</i>

376
00:29:26,280 --> 00:29:29,113
<i>Harry's wild about, I can't live without</i>

377
00:29:29,360 --> 00:29:31,999
<i>Harry's wild about me</i>

378
00:29:35,480 --> 00:29:37,516
<i>And like honey from the bee</i>

379
00:29:38,080 --> 00:29:41,038
<i>Say, I'm just wild about Harry</i>

380
00:29:41,640 --> 00:29:44,393
<i>Harry's wild about, I can't live without</i>

381
00:29:44,520 --> 00:29:49,196
<i>Harry's wild about me</i>

382
00:30:15,080 --> 00:30:18,356
<i>Tie everything down.</i>
<i>We are coming in to New York.</i>

383
00:30:28,240 --> 00:30:30,037
Come on, let's wake up.

384
00:30:38,480 --> 00:30:39,754
That's right.

385
00:30:47,440 --> 00:30:50,591
<i>Baby face, you got the cutest little</i>

386
00:30:57,240 --> 00:30:59,470
I'd say he was going to be just fine.

387
00:31:07,880 --> 00:31:10,599
- When did they bring me back?
- Night before last.

388
00:31:11,480 --> 00:31:13,869
Let's get some more of this down
before we talk.

389
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:17,629
- What was it that hit me?
- A little fever you picked up way back.

390
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:24,436
- You know, I have seen you someplace.
- You certainly have.

391
00:31:25,640 --> 00:31:27,198
- Where?
- Right here.

392
00:31:27,320 --> 00:31:28,639
- When?
- This morning.

393
00:31:28,760 --> 00:31:30,955
- This morning?
- When you woke up.

394
00:31:34,520 --> 00:31:36,636
I wouldn't forget you. You're pretty.

395
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:38,913
Just a baby face.

396
00:31:40,280 --> 00:31:42,077
- How do you know?
- You told me.

397
00:31:42,800 --> 00:31:44,791
- Me? When?
- This morning.

398
00:31:45,160 --> 00:31:47,628
- I said that?
- My friend, you sang it.

399
00:31:48,200 --> 00:31:51,590
- Do you have to keep doing that?
- Do you have to keep talking?

400
00:31:52,800 --> 00:31:55,951
- I sang it?
- More or less.

401
00:31:56,880 --> 00:32:01,078
- How was I, in good voice?
- You can do better, I imagine.

402
00:32:01,920 --> 00:32:04,514
You wouldn't know yourself.
You never heard me sing.

403
00:32:04,640 --> 00:32:06,358
Well, to be honest with you.

404
00:32:07,080 --> 00:32:09,878
- That was before your time, honey.
- A little bit.

405
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:12,992
Of course, you might have come across me
in the history books.

406
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:16,635
Now, I wouldn't say that.
I remember my folks talking about you.

407
00:32:17,640 --> 00:32:19,278
I'd like to meet them.

408
00:32:19,400 --> 00:32:22,790
But I don't imagine
I would be finding them up north.

409
00:32:23,520 --> 00:32:26,353
No, you wouldn't,
you would be finding them in Arkansas.

410
00:32:26,480 --> 00:32:29,870
Their name is Clark.
Their daughter's name is Ellen. Ellen Clark.

411
00:32:30,240 --> 00:32:32,549
It saves a lot more questions, doesn't it?

412
00:32:32,680 --> 00:32:33,795
Sure does.

413
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:36,912
Now we're going to lie back
and take a nice, long rest.

414
00:32:37,960 --> 00:32:40,554
- Honey, there's somebody I got to talk to.
- Tomorrow.

415
00:32:40,680 --> 00:32:43,353
Look, I just want to let Steve Martin
know I am all right.

416
00:32:43,480 --> 00:32:45,675
Mr. Martin knows. So does Papa.

417
00:32:45,920 --> 00:32:49,037
- Papa? He is here, too?
- He is positively darling.

418
00:32:49,160 --> 00:32:51,355
- Where are they? I want to see them.
- Tomorrow.

419
00:32:51,480 --> 00:32:55,632
Now look, baby, as far as I'm concerned,
tomorrow's always the middle of next year.

420
00:32:55,760 --> 00:32:58,991
Rushing around like that
is just about the worst thing for anybody.

421
00:32:59,120 --> 00:33:00,189
You don't say.

422
00:33:00,320 --> 00:33:02,311
You are bound to do
most everything wrong.

423
00:33:02,440 --> 00:33:04,590
Thanks, honey. Arkansas may feel that way...

424
00:33:04,720 --> 00:33:08,633
Now, you take animals back on the farm,
pigs for instance, never rushing around...

425
00:33:08,760 --> 00:33:12,548
except, of course, if they see a sudden
big shadow, an airplane or a hawk...

426
00:33:12,680 --> 00:33:15,069
that scares them
and gets them all confused.

427
00:33:15,200 --> 00:33:18,954
I've always believed people who
rush around get confused the same way.

428
00:33:19,560 --> 00:33:21,551
You were going to say something?

429
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:26,470
Yeah. I wouldn't care to see anybody today.

430
00:33:27,160 --> 00:33:29,151
Just as you say, Mr. Jolson.

431
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:32,195
My, we'll soon be smart as pigs.

432
00:33:43,880 --> 00:33:45,632
- Hello, Papa.
- Asa.

433
00:33:45,760 --> 00:33:47,716
- Steve.
- Jolson, loafing in bed.

434
00:33:47,840 --> 00:33:50,434
He looks fine.
I would positively know him anyplace.

435
00:33:50,560 --> 00:33:53,870
What gets me is how they tell a fever
from his normal condition.

436
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:55,877
- How do you feel, Asa?
- Okay.

437
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:59,117
- You had quite a tour for yourself?
- I gave it a whirl.

438
00:33:59,240 --> 00:34:00,832
Too big a whirl maybe.

439
00:34:01,960 --> 00:34:05,270
Tell them I'll be okay in a couple of weeks
and ready to hop off again.

440
00:34:05,400 --> 00:34:06,674
That is not wise, Asa.

441
00:34:06,800 --> 00:34:09,155
In fact, it sounds positively silly to me.

442
00:34:09,600 --> 00:34:12,910
Boys as sick as he's been are sent away
someplace for six months to rest.

443
00:34:13,040 --> 00:34:15,554
- Now, look...
- See? Ellen thinks so, too.

444
00:34:16,560 --> 00:34:19,233
- So it is Ellen already.
- Papa doesn't lose a minute.

445
00:34:19,360 --> 00:34:21,396
And, just what do you call him?

446
00:34:21,960 --> 00:34:24,030
- Cantor, mostly.
- So far, that is.

447
00:34:24,200 --> 00:34:26,714
That fever is going to be
in his system a long while.

448
00:34:26,840 --> 00:34:29,195
If he goes hopping around,
he's apt to come down bad.

449
00:34:29,320 --> 00:34:31,629
Where do you get
all those big answers, honey?

450
00:34:31,760 --> 00:34:34,593
By just relaxing, which is what
you ought to do for a change.

451
00:34:34,720 --> 00:34:37,518
Oh, brother!
You mean like back home, maybe?

452
00:34:39,080 --> 00:34:43,119
First thing my folks do almost anytime,
we just sit down and take off our shoes.

453
00:34:43,240 --> 00:34:46,118
Sister, his socks are even off
and that ain't helping.

454
00:34:46,240 --> 00:34:50,199
If he'd just forget how important he is
for once, he might do a sensible thing.

455
00:34:50,320 --> 00:34:52,709
- What do you mean by that?
- Just what I said.

456
00:34:52,840 --> 00:34:54,159
Now listen, sweetheart...

457
00:34:54,280 --> 00:34:57,477
whenever I've had a job to do,
I've always done it, see.

458
00:34:57,600 --> 00:34:58,953
That's what I mean.

459
00:34:59,080 --> 00:35:01,071
However, I just came in to say goodbye.

460
00:35:01,200 --> 00:35:02,918
- Goodbye?
- Where are you going?

461
00:35:03,040 --> 00:35:06,715
I'm transferred to an army hospital
in Arkansas. I'm leaving in the morning.

462
00:35:06,840 --> 00:35:09,912
- Walking out on me?
- You'll be just fine.

463
00:35:10,200 --> 00:35:12,236
You mean I won't be seeing you again?

464
00:35:12,360 --> 00:35:15,875
I go off duty in a few minutes,
and I'll have to pack the rest of the night.

465
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:17,956
- Goodbye, Mr. Martin.
- Good luck, Ellen.

466
00:35:18,080 --> 00:35:20,992
You can't make cracks at me
and walk out. I want to talk to you.

467
00:35:21,120 --> 00:35:23,554
- I really won't have time.
- That is too bad...

468
00:35:23,680 --> 00:35:27,878
because I thought on your last evening,
how nice if we could have dinner together.

469
00:35:28,320 --> 00:35:32,029
- Now, I will have to have dinner, won't I?
- Delightful.

470
00:35:32,360 --> 00:35:35,158
- At 7:00, shall we say?
- That'll be just fine.

471
00:35:52,080 --> 00:35:56,119
- And for dessert, Ellen?
- No dessert, just coffee, Papa.

472
00:35:56,440 --> 00:35:59,238
- Thank you.
- How will your daughter have her steak?

473
00:35:59,360 --> 00:36:00,349
Rare.

474
00:36:02,440 --> 00:36:04,829
Not my daughter, a friend.

475
00:36:05,240 --> 00:36:07,549
- I beg your pardon.
- "Papa," you see...

476
00:36:08,280 --> 00:36:11,397
- is a certain kind of modern term.
- I understand, sir.

477
00:36:13,480 --> 00:36:14,674
He understands.

478
00:36:18,520 --> 00:36:21,717
- Is this the kind of place you wanted?
- Exactly. Why not?

479
00:36:22,360 --> 00:36:25,113
- A little swanky.
- That's me tonight, swanky.

480
00:36:25,720 --> 00:36:28,359
You know, a waltz is my speciality.

481
00:36:28,680 --> 00:36:31,717
Of course, mine is not exactly
a cheek-to-cheek style...

482
00:36:31,840 --> 00:36:34,308
- but if you would honour me?
- I'd love it.

483
00:36:34,840 --> 00:36:38,196
But wouldn't you like to say
what you wanted to say to me first?

484
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:40,513
Remarkable girl.

485
00:36:41,520 --> 00:36:44,478
As a matter of fact,
I only wanted to thank you.

486
00:36:44,800 --> 00:36:47,758
- For what?
- The things you said to my son today.

487
00:36:49,400 --> 00:36:52,119
- A little brutal, wasn't I?
- But delightful.

488
00:36:53,160 --> 00:36:55,151
You know, he's a very nice boy.

489
00:36:55,520 --> 00:36:57,431
Of course, that's a father's opinion.

490
00:36:57,600 --> 00:36:59,909
- You could be right.
- Thank you.

491
00:37:00,320 --> 00:37:02,788
The only thing, he never learned how to live.

492
00:37:02,960 --> 00:37:06,236
You know, there was a look in his eyes
when you spoke to him that way...

493
00:37:06,360 --> 00:37:08,191
that I had never seen before.

494
00:37:08,320 --> 00:37:11,756
To me, it was like the first step
when a baby learns to walk.

495
00:37:12,120 --> 00:37:14,315
- Powerful baby, isn't he?
- Powerful.

496
00:37:14,480 --> 00:37:16,755
And he'll go right on singing
when he shouldn't.

497
00:37:16,880 --> 00:37:18,199
I'm afraid so.

498
00:37:18,600 --> 00:37:20,830
You know, in his condition
that could be bad.

499
00:37:20,960 --> 00:37:22,951
A baby doesn't walk in a day.

500
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:26,909
But the important thing, I have a feeling
he won't forget what you said.

501
00:37:27,280 --> 00:37:30,556
In fact, if I know my boy,
he will have to see you again.

502
00:37:31,440 --> 00:37:33,158
And if he does...

503
00:37:35,880 --> 00:37:38,075
I do not think I'd mind that at all.

504
00:37:42,320 --> 00:37:44,675
- And now?
- Delighted.

505
00:37:48,680 --> 00:37:52,195
- Is there something wrong?
- Just getting back into my shoes.

506
00:37:52,320 --> 00:37:53,594
Remarkable.

507
00:38:33,120 --> 00:38:37,079
You know, Ellen is right,
and I am through arguing with you.

508
00:38:37,520 --> 00:38:40,751
You're not going overseas again,
and that's all there is to it.

509
00:38:42,240 --> 00:38:43,559
You hear me?

510
00:38:44,520 --> 00:38:46,988
You don't know what a kick it was
to be singing again.

511
00:38:47,120 --> 00:38:50,351
- Sure, I do...
- Listen, I found out something.

512
00:38:51,160 --> 00:38:53,549
I have missed it every day since I quit.

513
00:38:54,360 --> 00:38:56,920
I realise now, I've only been half alive.

514
00:38:57,480 --> 00:39:00,472
All of a sudden I've got a terrific yen...

515
00:39:02,880 --> 00:39:06,759
What do you say, Steve, what if
I want to get back on Broadway again?

516
00:39:06,880 --> 00:39:09,952
- Do you think it is too late?
- What do you mean "too late"?

517
00:39:10,080 --> 00:39:11,479
Don't kid me, pal.

518
00:39:11,760 --> 00:39:14,354
Listen, the parade may pass some guys...

519
00:39:15,160 --> 00:39:17,515
but anytime you want to get back
at the business...

520
00:39:17,640 --> 00:39:20,234
- I wish I could believe it.
- You are crazy.

521
00:39:21,040 --> 00:39:23,793
All right, see what you can dig up
for me, Steve.

522
00:39:24,200 --> 00:39:25,872
A Broadway show, anything.

523
00:39:26,320 --> 00:39:28,276
- Will you go to work on it?
- Sure.

524
00:39:28,520 --> 00:39:30,476
- Right away?
- Yeah, right away.

525
00:39:30,680 --> 00:39:34,309
But meanwhile, you got to promise me
you're not going overseas again.

526
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:35,910
Okay.

527
00:39:36,560 --> 00:39:38,994
- Now we're getting someplace.
- All right.

528
00:39:39,480 --> 00:39:43,519
I'll stay home, and make a little tour
of these GI hospitals around the country.

529
00:39:43,640 --> 00:39:47,269
Now, wait. Ellen said to knock off everything
for at least six months.

530
00:39:47,840 --> 00:39:49,831
- Ellen did.
- Yeah, Ellen did.

531
00:39:50,360 --> 00:39:53,352
You know, Baby Face could be wrong
about something.

532
00:40:23,960 --> 00:40:26,474
<i>Baby face, you got the cutest little</i>

533
00:40:26,600 --> 00:40:28,716
<i>Oh, you've got a pretty face</i>

534
00:40:28,840 --> 00:40:31,035
<i>There's not another one</i>
<i>could take your place</i>

535
00:40:31,160 --> 00:40:32,991
<i>Ah, baby face</i>

536
00:40:33,760 --> 00:40:35,352
<i>My poor heart is jumping</i>

537
00:40:35,480 --> 00:40:37,869
<i>You sure have started something</i>
<i>Ah, baby face</i>

538
00:40:38,640 --> 00:40:42,519
<i>I'm up in heaven</i>
<i>when I'm in your fond embrace</i>

539
00:40:42,800 --> 00:40:45,837
<i>I didn't need a shove</i>
<i>'Cause I just fell in love</i>

540
00:40:46,120 --> 00:40:48,953
<i>With your pretty, ah, you baby face</i>

541
00:40:50,320 --> 00:40:51,355
<i>Baby face</i>

542
00:40:51,880 --> 00:40:54,599
<i>You got the cutest</i>
<i>Ah, you got a baby face</i>

543
00:40:55,040 --> 00:40:57,554
<i>There is not another one</i>
<i>could take your place</i>

544
00:40:57,680 --> 00:40:59,398
<i>Ah, baby face</i>

545
00:41:00,120 --> 00:41:02,315
<i>My poor heart is jumping, you sure have</i>

546
00:41:02,440 --> 00:41:04,112
<i>Ah, baby face</i>

547
00:41:05,080 --> 00:41:09,119
<i>I'm up in heaven</i>
<i>when I'm in your fond embrace</i>

548
00:41:09,280 --> 00:41:12,556
<i>You're like a breath of spring</i>
<i>When Jolie sings</i>

549
00:41:12,800 --> 00:41:16,873
<i>about your baby face</i>

550
00:41:29,480 --> 00:41:32,472
I don't know why
I'd want to see anybody like you again...

551
00:41:32,680 --> 00:41:35,797
but I couldn't wait to hit this place.
Now, isn't that daffy?

552
00:41:35,920 --> 00:41:38,309
Haven't you been singing too much lately?

553
00:41:38,440 --> 00:41:39,998
That's what I missed about you:

554
00:41:40,120 --> 00:41:42,873
Nobody to boss me around
and give me the answers.

555
00:41:43,240 --> 00:41:46,789
I am glad to see you.
In fact, I've been thinking about you.

556
00:41:47,040 --> 00:41:49,713
And, now and then, this is really daffy...

557
00:41:50,120 --> 00:41:53,590
I found myself thinking,
I could even get romantic about that pest.

558
00:41:53,720 --> 00:41:55,870
You know how your mind
runs away with you at times.

559
00:41:56,000 --> 00:41:58,434
Sure, mine does
with every other man I meet.

560
00:41:59,080 --> 00:42:00,308
It is fun.

561
00:42:00,840 --> 00:42:03,593
- But not exactly fun when I do it.
- Why not?

562
00:42:05,600 --> 00:42:08,990
For instance,
if the gal happens to be young, like you...

563
00:42:09,480 --> 00:42:11,630
I suddenly remember I am not so young.

564
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:14,116
I don't see what difference years make.

565
00:42:14,240 --> 00:42:16,390
I knew a couple once, same age.

566
00:42:16,920 --> 00:42:18,831
- It was terrible.
- It was?

567
00:42:20,560 --> 00:42:22,596
Then I remember something else.

568
00:42:22,720 --> 00:42:24,711
- I was married once.
- I know.

569
00:42:26,440 --> 00:42:28,431
- I made an awful flop of it.
- Why?

570
00:42:30,280 --> 00:42:32,350
It seems all I cared about was singing.

571
00:42:32,480 --> 00:42:34,630
That didn't give marriage much of a chance.

572
00:42:34,760 --> 00:42:37,513
You're afraid you might do
the same thing again?

573
00:42:37,960 --> 00:42:40,758
- I guess I do not have to worry about that.
- No?

574
00:42:41,360 --> 00:42:44,158
Because I walked out
on all the singing a long time ago.

575
00:42:44,280 --> 00:42:45,759
But you still want to.

576
00:42:46,480 --> 00:42:48,516
- Don't you?
- Yeah.

577
00:42:49,480 --> 00:42:53,189
But the point is, the world
ain't exactly clamouring for me anymore.

578
00:42:53,520 --> 00:42:57,513
Well, now, I am just sure
the world would again, if you wanted it to.

579
00:42:59,280 --> 00:43:00,554
I like you.

580
00:43:02,280 --> 00:43:05,750
And if it does, just see
that you get more out of life than singing.

581
00:43:05,880 --> 00:43:09,031
I will try and remember that, baby,
if it ever happens.

582
00:43:10,040 --> 00:43:12,554
I am afraid I would
need a little help, though.

583
00:43:12,680 --> 00:43:15,877
I might have to ask somebody like you
where to start.

584
00:43:16,640 --> 00:43:20,349
Now, if I am not around,
you just try relaxing.

585
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:22,479
Take off my shoes?

586
00:43:22,840 --> 00:43:26,310
Anything you get fun out of,
you just go right ahead and do it.

587
00:43:27,440 --> 00:43:30,477
Right now, it would be terrific fun
to kiss you.

588
00:43:36,160 --> 00:43:37,513
Then I would.

589
00:44:30,480 --> 00:44:32,755
What complications, Steve? What is it?

590
00:44:34,400 --> 00:44:37,949
A lung was infected. They had to operate.
Cut out the bad spot.

591
00:44:38,320 --> 00:44:41,392
<i>Now, he's gonna be fine.</i>
<i>He's in good hands.</i>

592
00:44:41,680 --> 00:44:43,591
<i>- Cantor? Hello?</i>
- Yes, Steve.

593
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:45,558
Believe me, will you?

594
00:44:45,680 --> 00:44:47,830
There is no sense
your making a trip out here.

595
00:44:47,960 --> 00:44:50,952
I'll phone you again tomorrow. Goodbye.

596
00:44:58,320 --> 00:45:01,153
The doc says you got a constitution
like an ox.

597
00:45:01,400 --> 00:45:03,914
You're gonna mend so fast,
nobody will believe it.

598
00:45:04,040 --> 00:45:05,473
Do you know something else?

599
00:45:05,600 --> 00:45:09,354
He says you are as much all there today
as you ever were in your life.

600
00:45:11,760 --> 00:45:13,557
- Hello, Ellen.
- Hello, Steve.

601
00:45:22,240 --> 00:45:25,471
I thought you might be needing
some answers right now.

602
00:45:26,280 --> 00:45:29,670
Just a good lung, baby. Got one of those?

603
00:45:32,400 --> 00:45:34,277
You are breathing, honey.

604
00:45:34,440 --> 00:45:37,318
Now, who would want a man
to do more than that?

605
00:45:48,080 --> 00:45:50,640
I don't believe it. Let me talk to him.

606
00:45:50,960 --> 00:45:52,757
He doesn't believe it.

607
00:45:53,920 --> 00:45:56,912
Hello, Papa. You know this gal
gets her way about everything.

608
00:45:57,240 --> 00:46:01,074
But yesterday, out of the hospital,
today married. Is this wise?

609
00:46:02,320 --> 00:46:05,039
Never mind. It's lovely. Let me talk to her.

610
00:46:05,640 --> 00:46:06,550
Here.

611
00:46:07,240 --> 00:46:08,878
- Hello, Papa.
<i>- Ellen.</i>

612
00:46:09,200 --> 00:46:10,792
It's really "Papa" now.

613
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:12,149
Yes, it's wonderful.

614
00:46:12,280 --> 00:46:13,599
You should see this ring.

615
00:46:13,720 --> 00:46:16,951
I got some orchids. If they were any bigger,
I couldn't see around them.

616
00:46:17,080 --> 00:46:19,355
I must see both of you.
I am coming out there.

617
00:46:19,480 --> 00:46:20,356
<i>When?</i>

618
00:46:20,480 --> 00:46:22,311
After the high holidays, in two weeks.

619
00:46:22,640 --> 00:46:24,756
Good. We'll have a nice place
waiting for you.

620
00:46:24,880 --> 00:46:26,996
In fact, we are moving into a house today.

621
00:46:27,280 --> 00:46:30,670
- You've got a house already?
- A beautiful one, out in the valley.

622
00:46:30,800 --> 00:46:33,917
It's been rented up to a few months ago,
but we can get into it now.

623
00:46:34,040 --> 00:46:35,837
It's Al's house.

624
00:46:36,480 --> 00:46:39,233
- AI's house?
- Yes, the one Julie built.

625
00:46:40,120 --> 00:46:42,509
<i>Imagine looking for a place in these times.</i>

626
00:46:42,720 --> 00:46:45,951
<i>And one sitting out there,</i>
<i>just as vacant and pretty as can be.</i>

627
00:46:46,080 --> 00:46:48,719
It doesn't make sense,
at least not in Arkansas.

628
00:46:48,840 --> 00:46:50,432
You understand, don't you, Papa?

629
00:46:50,560 --> 00:46:51,754
Yes. I think I do.

630
00:46:51,880 --> 00:46:53,950
You get out here when you said,
in two weeks.

631
00:46:54,080 --> 00:46:55,479
We'll be expecting you.

632
00:46:55,600 --> 00:46:58,239
Yes. Goodbye.

633
00:46:58,600 --> 00:46:59,999
Goodbye, Papa.

634
00:47:03,840 --> 00:47:05,398
Let's get moving.

635
00:47:17,240 --> 00:47:18,992
Now, isn't this a dill?

636
00:47:19,120 --> 00:47:20,678
- Dill?
- Beautiful.

637
00:47:20,920 --> 00:47:22,717
Don't you understand English?

638
00:47:22,840 --> 00:47:26,515
I haven't had time to do much here.
But I'll get going in a couple of days.

639
00:47:26,640 --> 00:47:28,676
First thing, we'll get a little fresh air.

640
00:47:28,800 --> 00:47:31,109
A little dusting wouldn't do any harm.

641
00:47:32,480 --> 00:47:34,630
Aren't you two in pretty poses?

642
00:47:35,200 --> 00:47:37,589
How about getting
some of those bags upstairs?

643
00:47:37,720 --> 00:47:38,869
Steve, you do it.

644
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:41,639
Mr. Jolson, you come over here
and sit down.

645
00:47:49,880 --> 00:47:52,269
I've been hoping
somebody can play checkers here.

646
00:47:52,400 --> 00:47:54,550
I can keep myself in pin money.

647
00:47:59,480 --> 00:48:00,833
Al, honey...

648
00:48:01,760 --> 00:48:03,716
it's cruel to bring you back to this house.

649
00:48:03,840 --> 00:48:06,479
- No, baby.
- I know it is. I must be crazy.

650
00:48:06,840 --> 00:48:09,752
- Fine time to tell me.
- I just didn't want any ghosts around.

651
00:48:09,880 --> 00:48:11,632
I wanted you to wrestle with them here...

652
00:48:11,760 --> 00:48:13,637
so you'd know
where you stood about the past...

653
00:48:13,760 --> 00:48:15,990
and so I would know, too.
That's what I thought.

654
00:48:16,120 --> 00:48:17,872
- That's right, baby.
- No, it isn't.

655
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:19,911
Look, if there are any ghosts around...

656
00:48:20,040 --> 00:48:22,508
this is the place to make them
come out and fight.

657
00:48:22,640 --> 00:48:24,517
That's what I'm getting to like about you.

658
00:48:24,640 --> 00:48:27,552
- You're just saying that.
- And I'm meaning that.

659
00:48:29,440 --> 00:48:32,113
Promise me, if this house gets you down...

660
00:48:32,560 --> 00:48:35,950
when you can't take it anymore,
I want you to tell me straight out.

661
00:48:36,080 --> 00:48:39,197
Like I could keep something from you
if I wanted to.

662
00:48:42,880 --> 00:48:44,518
I also move pianos.

663
00:48:44,800 --> 00:48:47,792
And my heavy cleaning
is in demand all over town.

664
00:48:48,200 --> 00:48:50,873
Come on, you two.
You've got years to do that.

665
00:48:53,800 --> 00:48:55,916
Here, I'll take a couple of those.
No arguments.

666
00:48:56,040 --> 00:48:57,678
All right, you win.

667
00:48:58,160 --> 00:49:00,071
Look when she lets me win.

668
00:49:00,840 --> 00:49:03,115
Say, anybody thought about getting help?

669
00:49:03,240 --> 00:49:05,276
How would you like to have
Henry and Alice back?

670
00:49:05,400 --> 00:49:08,437
- Where would you find Henry and Alice?
- Already found them.

671
00:49:08,560 --> 00:49:09,834
They'll be here tonight.

672
00:49:09,960 --> 00:49:12,633
Quit their jobs and are flying back here
on broomsticks.

673
00:49:36,600 --> 00:49:39,114
He could go on listening to the radio
like that forever.

674
00:49:39,240 --> 00:49:42,118
- Likes music I guess.
- I wouldn't be surprised.

675
00:49:44,440 --> 00:49:47,796
He looks to me like a man about ready
to go back to work.

676
00:49:48,360 --> 00:49:49,679
You mean, sing?

677
00:49:50,160 --> 00:49:52,628
- Don't you think he can, Steve?
- Sure.

678
00:49:53,440 --> 00:49:56,716
- But he doesn't think so, does he?
- It's only natural.

679
00:49:57,000 --> 00:49:59,639
- That lung's all healed.
- I suppose it is.

680
00:49:59,960 --> 00:50:01,791
I can see why he'd be afraid.

681
00:50:01,920 --> 00:50:04,753
Or is he afraid
that nobody wants to hear him?

682
00:50:05,240 --> 00:50:07,959
In that case, he'd tell himself
it was his lung, wouldn't he?

683
00:50:08,080 --> 00:50:11,152
Why worry about it, Ellen?
He's happy enough, isn't he?

684
00:50:11,280 --> 00:50:14,033
Not if what he wants is to be back at work.

685
00:50:14,320 --> 00:50:17,392
- Do you think he does?
- This is a laugh.

686
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:20,389
There was one woman once
who wanted him like this...

687
00:50:20,520 --> 00:50:22,795
living a little and not singing his head off.

688
00:50:22,920 --> 00:50:24,751
And here you are now...

689
00:50:26,640 --> 00:50:29,916
- Not exactly a tactful guy, am I?
- Yes, you are, Steve.

690
00:50:30,720 --> 00:50:32,756
I really want him to do both.

691
00:50:33,560 --> 00:50:34,879
All I know...

692
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:38,549
it can't be good when the natural part
of a man is just moulding away.

693
00:50:39,960 --> 00:50:42,190
You didn't answer me.
I asked you if you thought...

694
00:50:42,320 --> 00:50:45,198
- he'd like to be back singing again.
- Of course he would.

695
00:50:45,320 --> 00:50:48,551
He'd like to be right back
in the middle of show business again.

696
00:50:48,680 --> 00:50:50,636
- He said so?
- Yes.

697
00:50:50,880 --> 00:50:54,873
Just before he started that hospital tour.
Told me to go to work on it.

698
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:59,596
There is something I haven't told anybody,
and wouldn't tell him in a million years.

699
00:50:59,720 --> 00:51:02,917
I did go to work, and the answer is:
Nobody wants him.

700
00:51:03,040 --> 00:51:06,157
Broadway, radio,
nobody would risk a nickel on him.

701
00:51:06,400 --> 00:51:09,437
A new crop of singers
has pushed Jolson right off the map.

702
00:51:09,560 --> 00:51:12,791
If he tries for a comeback,
he'll take the beating of his life.

703
00:51:12,920 --> 00:51:16,071
It would kill him
to have to face the truth about it.

704
00:51:24,400 --> 00:51:26,118
So do you see what I mean, Ellen?

705
00:51:26,240 --> 00:51:30,552
If he thinks he's through due to his lung,
even if he's lying to himself a little...

706
00:51:30,680 --> 00:51:33,638
it's the kindest thing
that could have happened.

707
00:51:39,960 --> 00:51:42,315
Do you understand what I'm saying?

708
00:51:49,320 --> 00:51:50,878
See, as good as my word.

709
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:53,434
I tell you right now, you'll stay a long time.

710
00:51:53,560 --> 00:51:55,676
If I like it here, I won't argue.

711
00:51:55,800 --> 00:51:58,951
- Henry! I don't believe it.
- It's nice to see you again, Cantor.

712
00:51:59,080 --> 00:52:01,230
- My goodness, it's a long time.
- Many years.

713
00:52:01,360 --> 00:52:04,158
- You don't look a day older.
- Neither do you.

714
00:52:04,360 --> 00:52:06,749
What a comfort we are to each other.

715
00:52:11,960 --> 00:52:14,110
I don't have to ask if you are happy.

716
00:52:14,320 --> 00:52:16,151
- I do not know.
- Miserable?

717
00:52:17,280 --> 00:52:20,477
Husband out of work,
lazing around the house all day.

718
00:52:20,680 --> 00:52:21,829
Not good.

719
00:52:22,600 --> 00:52:24,989
Steve says he isn't wanted anymore...

720
00:52:25,120 --> 00:52:27,918
and he'd take a beating
if he tried to sing again.

721
00:52:28,040 --> 00:52:30,634
I am wondering, Papa,
which would be the worse beating:

722
00:52:30,760 --> 00:52:33,433
Trying or just never singing again at all.

723
00:52:35,760 --> 00:52:37,591
It's hard to say, Ellen.

724
00:52:38,040 --> 00:52:40,508
You mean, if I were smart,
I'd mind my own business.

725
00:52:40,640 --> 00:52:42,392
Women in love never do.

726
00:52:43,520 --> 00:52:44,794
Is that bad?

727
00:52:45,600 --> 00:52:46,953
Bad. Good.

728
00:52:47,880 --> 00:52:49,233
It's history.

729
00:52:50,840 --> 00:52:55,038
You know, it's nice you're here, Papa.
I've been sort of waiting for you.

730
00:52:55,520 --> 00:52:57,192
Dinner must be ready.

731
00:53:01,840 --> 00:53:04,035
We have to get some
special entertainment for Papa.

732
00:53:04,160 --> 00:53:05,513
Me? Entertainment?

733
00:53:05,640 --> 00:53:08,200
Don't you like to go dancing
in swanky restaurants?

734
00:53:08,320 --> 00:53:10,311
That was in my younger days.

735
00:53:11,080 --> 00:53:13,753
There's a benefit show
for the Community Chest next week.

736
00:53:13,880 --> 00:53:16,678
A lot of big stars will be on the program.
Would you like to go?

737
00:53:16,800 --> 00:53:19,473
- Nice. Very nice.
- I'll see that we're there.

738
00:53:19,640 --> 00:53:20,959
- AI?
- Sure. Fine.

739
00:53:21,600 --> 00:53:24,910
To give Papa a real thrill,
you ought to be on that stage that night.

740
00:53:25,040 --> 00:53:27,395
- What doing, telling jokes?
- What you always did.

741
00:53:27,520 --> 00:53:29,397
- Yeah?
- Just a song or two.

742
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:32,560
- Bet you one would be enough.
- I don't know.

743
00:53:32,680 --> 00:53:35,558
If you sound as good as you do
when you sing in the bathroom.

744
00:53:35,680 --> 00:53:37,875
Bathroom? You just hum a little.

745
00:53:38,320 --> 00:53:40,914
With all that resonance in there,
you sound like Caruso.

746
00:53:41,040 --> 00:53:43,190
Don't you know
that's why people sing in there?

747
00:53:43,320 --> 00:53:46,312
- And you especially like it, don't you?
- Love it.

748
00:53:46,440 --> 00:53:49,159
Why don't you try coming out
of the bathroom for a change?

749
00:53:49,280 --> 00:53:50,952
The public might love it, too.

750
00:53:51,080 --> 00:53:53,355
You're trying to get me back to work
or something?

751
00:53:53,480 --> 00:53:57,439
I don't want a man lazing around the house
all the rest of his life.

752
00:53:57,720 --> 00:53:59,950
You sound like you're only half kidding.

753
00:54:00,080 --> 00:54:02,150
- About half.
- Only half?

754
00:54:03,480 --> 00:54:06,392
In that case, tell you what to do, Steve.

755
00:54:06,760 --> 00:54:09,115
You hop to New York
and get a show together for me.

756
00:54:09,240 --> 00:54:11,515
Tell them not to worry
about my recent operation.

757
00:54:11,640 --> 00:54:14,791
Of course, I haven't got the breath
for those high notes anymore...

758
00:54:14,920 --> 00:54:17,957
Or radio. That'd be better.
They ought to be wild to have me.

759
00:54:18,080 --> 00:54:19,752
A name like Jolson...

760
00:54:19,880 --> 00:54:22,678
a name that bobbysoxers never heard of,
that's true...

761
00:54:22,800 --> 00:54:26,076
and a style of singing
that went out with button shoes.

762
00:54:26,840 --> 00:54:29,400
Or did you find that out already, Steve?

763
00:54:29,720 --> 00:54:31,676
- Find out what?
- You know what.

764
00:54:31,800 --> 00:54:33,631
I was gonna make a big comeback.

765
00:54:33,760 --> 00:54:36,593
What did you find out?
Bet they were dying to have me back.

766
00:54:36,720 --> 00:54:39,792
I really didn't get started,
but there was a lot of interest.

767
00:54:39,920 --> 00:54:40,989
I see.

768
00:54:41,360 --> 00:54:44,158
Of course, without your name in lights
on Broadway...

769
00:54:44,280 --> 00:54:47,750
and making oodles of money,
I guess it wouldn't be singing.

770
00:54:48,200 --> 00:54:49,474
What do you mean?

771
00:54:49,600 --> 00:54:51,636
During the war,
you sang just to do something...

772
00:54:51,760 --> 00:54:54,911
- for the fun of it.
- Sure. But that was then.

773
00:54:55,280 --> 00:54:58,989
Even now, I can't see why you have
to be worried about a little old benefit.

774
00:54:59,120 --> 00:55:01,873
There's gonna be 5,000 people
at that little old benefit...

775
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:04,639
in a big theatre. Not a thing to worry about.

776
00:55:04,760 --> 00:55:06,591
Except if I can put two notes together...

777
00:55:06,720 --> 00:55:08,870
and whether they can hear me
past the second row.

778
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:10,672
You can prove that to yourself.

779
00:55:10,800 --> 00:55:12,791
Come on. What's the use talking about it?

780
00:55:12,920 --> 00:55:15,115
Okay. If you're sure you can't.

781
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:17,228
What if I wasn't sure?

782
00:55:17,360 --> 00:55:20,875
I don't see anybody breaking down doors
to get me on that benefit.

783
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:24,356
- Maybe if they knew you wanted to...
- Let's drop it, baby.

784
00:55:28,360 --> 00:55:29,349
Sure.

785
00:55:29,840 --> 00:55:32,513
How about a game
of checkers tonight, Papa?

786
00:55:33,200 --> 00:55:36,237
No thank you, Ellen.
I couldn't eat another thing.

787
00:56:05,400 --> 00:56:08,517
- Pretty tune.
- That's the big one right now.

788
00:56:09,600 --> 00:56:11,716
Made to order for these crooners.

789
00:56:11,840 --> 00:56:15,276
They sure sing this stuff today
nice and easy, don't they?

790
00:56:19,240 --> 00:56:22,994
Who says you need
all the voice in the world to put a song over.

791
00:56:36,240 --> 00:56:39,357
<i>'Cause I only have eyes</i>

792
00:56:40,160 --> 00:56:43,789
<i>for you, dear</i>

793
00:56:44,640 --> 00:56:47,438
<i>The moon may be high</i>

794
00:56:48,400 --> 00:56:51,870
<i>But I can't see a thing in the sky</i>

795
00:56:52,440 --> 00:56:55,671
<i>'Cause I only have eyes</i>

796
00:56:56,200 --> 00:57:00,159
<i>for you</i>

797
00:57:01,200 --> 00:57:05,876
<i>I don't know if we're in a garden</i>

798
00:57:09,040 --> 00:57:14,194
<i>Or on a crowded avenue</i>

799
00:57:14,560 --> 00:57:18,951
<i>You are here, so am I</i>

800
00:57:19,880 --> 00:57:23,236
<i>Maybe millions of people pass by</i>

801
00:57:23,840 --> 00:57:26,991
<i>But they all disappear</i>

802
00:57:27,520 --> 00:57:30,159
<i>from view</i>

803
00:57:30,480 --> 00:57:35,076
<i>And I</i>

804
00:57:35,400 --> 00:57:39,439
<i>only have eyes</i>

805
00:57:39,960 --> 00:57:45,512
<i>for you</i>

806
00:57:54,160 --> 00:57:56,230
Must be the resonance in here.

807
00:57:57,080 --> 00:57:58,957
Resonance, of course.

808
00:58:02,160 --> 00:58:05,277
Okay, Steve.
If they can use me on that benefit.

809
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:13,639
- You win.
- Another game, Papa?

810
00:58:14,560 --> 00:58:16,198
Another game, Steve?

811
00:58:21,560 --> 00:58:23,630
I'm glad he's in shape again, Steve.

812
00:58:23,760 --> 00:58:26,718
But actually, I got too big a list of stars,
right now.

813
00:58:26,840 --> 00:58:29,638
Every year, the program's too long.
You know how it is.

814
00:58:29,760 --> 00:58:31,113
Yeah, I know.

815
00:58:31,280 --> 00:58:33,475
If you could still get a big name,
you'd grab it.

816
00:58:33,600 --> 00:58:35,272
You just don't want Jolson.

817
00:58:35,400 --> 00:58:37,595
Ten years ago,
you'd be kissing his feet to get him.

818
00:58:37,720 --> 00:58:40,917
Be reasonable. All I'm trying to do
is get a big turnout for a benefit.

819
00:58:41,040 --> 00:58:43,076
I've got to have names that mean something.

820
00:58:43,200 --> 00:58:44,997
I don't care what you got to have.

821
00:58:45,120 --> 00:58:47,111
When Al Jolson says he'll appear...

822
00:58:47,240 --> 00:58:50,915
the guy you and I remember when he was
bigger than your whole list put together...

823
00:58:51,040 --> 00:58:53,395
I'm not going to that guy
with some lame excuse...

824
00:58:53,520 --> 00:58:55,476
that adds up to only one thing:

825
00:58:55,600 --> 00:58:56,953
He's not wanted.

826
00:58:57,080 --> 00:59:00,595
I can't do it, Charlie.
And you're not gonna make me do it.

827
00:59:02,600 --> 00:59:04,477
All right, Steve. He's on.

828
00:59:44,320 --> 00:59:46,231
- Hi.
- Good morning, baby.

829
00:59:47,720 --> 00:59:50,553
Today is the day. Is it in the paper?

830
00:59:51,320 --> 00:59:52,719
Let me see it.

831
01:00:05,920 --> 01:00:09,151
My name is a little hard to find, baby.
It is at the bottom there.

832
01:00:09,280 --> 01:00:11,350
"And many others." That's me.

833
01:00:18,800 --> 01:00:21,360
- Nice day?
- Yeah. Real nice.

834
01:00:52,320 --> 01:00:54,311
This is going way over time.

835
01:01:03,800 --> 01:01:07,190
- Look at the time, Ralph. Let's go.
- No, wait. Please.

836
01:01:07,800 --> 01:01:10,155
There's one fellow I've got to hear.

837
01:01:12,960 --> 01:01:16,794
It's great to go on near the finish,
except there won't be any audience.

838
01:01:29,240 --> 01:01:30,719
Where is everybody?

839
01:01:32,160 --> 01:01:35,357
Seriously, I guess I've got
a few old friends out there.

840
01:01:35,480 --> 01:01:37,869
Who else would be
hanging around at this hour?

841
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:41,788
So I'm gonna sing you an old one,
just one and let you go home.

842
01:01:42,840 --> 01:01:44,319
By the way, a nice quiet one...

843
01:01:44,440 --> 01:01:46,829
so as we won't disturb the people
who sleep.

844
01:01:48,120 --> 01:01:50,270
Just like we rehearsed it, pal.

845
01:02:03,600 --> 01:02:08,355
<i>Climb upon my knee, sonny boy</i>

846
01:02:10,520 --> 01:02:15,753
<i>Though you are only three, sonny boy</i>

847
01:02:17,200 --> 01:02:19,395
<i>You have no way of knowing</i>

848
01:02:19,960 --> 01:02:22,679
<i>There's no way of showing</i>

849
01:02:23,320 --> 01:02:25,550
<i>What you mean to me</i>

850
01:02:25,760 --> 01:02:31,437
<i>sonny boy</i>

851
01:02:34,080 --> 01:02:38,710
<i>When there are grey skies</i>

852
01:02:39,880 --> 01:02:44,556
<i>I don't mind the grey skies</i>

853
01:02:46,120 --> 01:02:48,873
<i>You make them blue</i>

854
01:02:49,560 --> 01:02:53,269
<i>sonny boy</i>

855
01:02:56,800 --> 01:02:59,997
<i>Friends, friends may forsake me</i>

856
01:03:01,600 --> 01:03:05,991
<i>Let them, let them all forsake me</i>

857
01:03:07,400 --> 01:03:09,994
<i>I still have you</i>

858
01:03:11,640 --> 01:03:15,030
<i>sonny boy</i>

859
01:03:18,240 --> 01:03:20,117
<i>You are sent from heaven</i>

860
01:03:22,040 --> 01:03:24,634
<i>and I know your worth</i>

861
01:03:26,840 --> 01:03:29,638
<i>You have made a heaven</i>

862
01:03:30,920 --> 01:03:36,631
<i>for me here on earth</i>

863
01:03:42,240 --> 01:03:46,199
<i>And the angels grew lonely</i>

864
01:03:47,320 --> 01:03:51,916
<i>Took you, because they were lonely</i>

865
01:03:52,600 --> 01:03:56,479
<i>I am lonely, too</i>

866
01:03:56,960 --> 01:04:02,671
<i>sonny boy</i>

867
01:04:25,240 --> 01:04:27,470
Nothing like singing for a lot of old-timers.

868
01:04:27,600 --> 01:04:31,752
- I liked it, and I am not an old-timer.
- But you happen to be very nice.

869
01:04:33,600 --> 01:04:35,670
Better watch the road, honey.

870
01:04:39,480 --> 01:04:42,916
Amazing how he can still get you
with a corny old song like that.

871
01:04:43,760 --> 01:04:46,320
I think he can still get anybody,
singing anything.

872
01:04:46,440 --> 01:04:48,954
Singing styles have changed a little, Ralph.

873
01:04:49,080 --> 01:04:51,469
I don't know about that.
But I know one thing.

874
01:04:51,600 --> 01:04:55,195
His voice is better now than it ever was,
warmer, more heart.

875
01:04:56,160 --> 01:04:57,513
Oddly enough...

876
01:04:57,800 --> 01:05:01,634
a certain newspaper columnist brought me
a picture idea a few weeks ago:

877
01:05:01,760 --> 01:05:03,432
<i>The Life of Jolson</i>.

878
01:05:03,560 --> 01:05:06,313
He had to bring that idea to me, an old fan.

879
01:05:06,840 --> 01:05:09,957
Listening to that voice tonight,
I kept thinking...

880
01:05:10,640 --> 01:05:14,110
if you could give people a real chance
to hear him again...

881
01:05:16,560 --> 01:05:18,437
Bit of a tough one, though.

882
01:05:53,160 --> 01:05:55,515
- It was a beating, wasn't it?
- What?

883
01:05:56,360 --> 01:05:59,318
This whole thing tonight
that I plagued you into doing.

884
01:05:59,480 --> 01:06:03,189
It wasn't anything, honey.
I just said to myself:

885
01:06:03,320 --> 01:06:06,232
"Now in Arkansas, we'd look at it this way."

886
01:06:06,440 --> 01:06:08,715
I know I'm not headlining this show.

887
01:06:08,840 --> 01:06:10,956
I got a hunch they don't even want me on it.

888
01:06:11,080 --> 01:06:13,640
I know half this crowd
didn't want to hear me sing.

889
01:06:13,760 --> 01:06:17,548
The other half is only sticking around
for old times' sake. I know all that.

890
01:06:17,680 --> 01:06:21,912
I didn't come here for glory.
I just came to do something I wanted to do.

891
01:06:26,520 --> 01:06:27,873
I don't care.

892
01:06:28,160 --> 01:06:30,628
You were absolutely marvellous tonight.

893
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:36,151
There you are.
And I got something out of my system.

894
01:06:36,840 --> 01:06:40,833
In fact, a couple more jobs like tonight,
and I'm a pretty happy man.

895
01:06:41,160 --> 01:06:43,276
So what are you talking about?

896
01:06:54,240 --> 01:06:55,309
Hello?

897
01:06:56,080 --> 01:06:57,354
Yes, it is.

898
01:06:57,840 --> 01:06:59,353
That's all right.

899
01:06:59,760 --> 01:07:00,749
Who?

900
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:04,672
Oh, yes. How are you?

901
01:07:10,880 --> 01:07:13,110
You really liked it, didn't you, pal?

902
01:07:13,240 --> 01:07:15,356
It's nice of you to call and tell me.

903
01:07:15,480 --> 01:07:17,914
No, that's okay. I hadn't gone to bed yet.

904
01:07:19,440 --> 01:07:20,793
Thanks a lot.

905
01:07:22,720 --> 01:07:24,233
Why, sure.

906
01:07:25,120 --> 01:07:27,190
Anytime. I am generally home.

907
01:07:28,920 --> 01:07:30,751
Thanks again. Goodnight.

908
01:07:33,000 --> 01:07:33,910
Bryant?

909
01:07:41,480 --> 01:07:43,277
How are you, Mr. Bryant?

910
01:07:43,480 --> 01:07:47,268
You still don't know me, do you?
Colonel Bryant, the Aleutians.

911
01:07:48,360 --> 01:07:50,078
- Duluth, Minnesota.
- That's right.

912
01:07:50,200 --> 01:07:53,909
If it ain't old Duluth! It had to be an old fan.
I'm glad to see you.

913
01:07:54,040 --> 01:07:56,554
Come on out and meet the family.
They will love you.

914
01:07:56,680 --> 01:07:58,033
They are fans of mine, too.

915
01:07:58,160 --> 01:08:00,799
And, brother, how many members
of that club are still around?

916
01:08:00,920 --> 01:08:03,229
Meet Colonel Bryant. My wife, Mrs. Jolson.

917
01:08:03,360 --> 01:08:04,679
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

918
01:08:04,800 --> 01:08:07,712
- My father and Steve Martin.
- How are you, sir?

919
01:08:08,600 --> 01:08:10,397
- Glad to know you, sir.
- How do you do?

920
01:08:10,520 --> 01:08:13,671
This fellow phones in the middle
of the night to tell me I am terrific.

921
01:08:13,800 --> 01:08:15,552
- Don't you love him?
- Mad about him.

922
01:08:15,680 --> 01:08:17,113
See. Old homely.

923
01:08:17,240 --> 01:08:19,913
- Sit down. Stay for lunch with us.
- Thanks. I'd like to.

924
01:08:20,040 --> 01:08:23,589
You'll want him to stay for dinner, too,
'cause up in the Aleutians...

925
01:08:23,720 --> 01:08:26,314
if it hadn't been for the pat on the back
he gave me...

926
01:08:26,440 --> 01:08:29,830
I was worried and scared stiff.
He picked me right up off the floor.

927
01:08:29,960 --> 01:08:32,918
In fact, you can bring your clothes
and move in, Colonel Bryant.

928
01:08:33,040 --> 01:08:35,793
Let's forget the "Colonel."
I'm just a picture producer again.

929
01:08:35,920 --> 01:08:39,276
I didn't tell you that.
Came from Hollywood all the time.

930
01:08:39,600 --> 01:08:41,591
How does it feel to be back making movies?

931
01:08:41,720 --> 01:08:45,076
They are always tough,
except when you get a really exciting idea.

932
01:08:45,200 --> 01:08:48,317
- And I got one last night, listening to you.
- Yeah?

933
01:08:48,560 --> 01:08:50,949
I didn't sleep much.
This morning I was still at it.

934
01:08:51,080 --> 01:08:53,435
So I thought I'd come over
and talk to you about it.

935
01:08:53,560 --> 01:08:55,710
- What's that?
- A motion picture.

936
01:08:56,680 --> 01:08:59,752
You mean you want me
to play a part or something? Me?

937
01:08:59,880 --> 01:09:02,599
No. A picture about you. Your whole career.

938
01:09:04,200 --> 01:09:06,919
- Sound crazy?
- My friend, as goofy as can be.

939
01:09:07,040 --> 01:09:08,268
- Why?
- Why?

940
01:09:11,120 --> 01:09:14,157
- Last night should tell you why.
- Last night brought me out here.

941
01:09:14,280 --> 01:09:16,635
Yeah, you and a few hundred others.

942
01:09:17,400 --> 01:09:20,073
But you make pictures today
for a whole new generation.

943
01:09:20,200 --> 01:09:22,589
They buy the tickets.
What's in this one for them?

944
01:09:22,720 --> 01:09:25,359
The story of the biggest man
in entertainment for 30 years...

945
01:09:25,480 --> 01:09:26,799
